'''Level 321''', also known as "'''Amaranthine Inn'''", is the current 322nd level found in the [[Backrooms Wiki|Backrooms]].
==Description==
{{Blurimage|file=Level321bright.png|caption=A brightly lit hallway.|hovertext=𝚏𝚒𝚐 1.0}}
'''Level 321''', also known as “'''Amaranthine Inn''',” is an extensive, lavender-themed hotel complex with elongated halls and colossal salons. The walls are burdened with violet tones, whereas the floors are often covered with dark, murky carpet; such textiles remain spotless and immaculate. The circular ceiling lights leave the hotel, casting an unwavering lavender glow into the hotel’s interior, where one often portrays a sense of despondency. Each hall, let alone, is disproportionately narrow, making one incapable of feeling at ease. The surrounding walls are adorned with ornate paintings that blend seamlessly into the surrounding decor, depicting unfamiliar people, landscapes, and ceremonies. Despite the absence of any documented movement, prolonged eye contact frequently immobilizes wanderers, accompanied by indistinct whispers or distant conversations whose meanings seem to differ among individuals.

The layout of '''Level 321''' is rather perpetual, dependent on one’s memory and illusion: a series of interconnected simulant hallways shifting simultaneously, adjoining jointly while forming repetitive, symmetrical fractal patterns. Similar to recollection, structure furtively morphs into the most vaguely remembered, recurring until a form of confabulation occurs, wherein halls diverge into a pristine iteration. Therewithal, navigating remains a hassle; unwary progression leads to getting lost, resulting in a lonely, fraught death. Salons, on the other hand, are colossal; they lead into various rooms, such as ballrooms, buffets, and lobbies. Salons are seemingly more stable and straightforward, inosculating variants as well as bisecting them altogether.
{{Blurimage|file=Level321narrow.png|caption=A winding, narrow hallway.|hovertext=𝚏𝚒𝚐 2.0}}
In principle, salon variations are indifferent in outline, alongside tremendously vast rooms with scarcely furnished interiors. The layout of salons is much more stable yet insecure; traversing salons, one may encounter ambient differences throughout the surroundings. Although characteristic furnishings are present in all types of salons, they insidiously evolve into barren, singular rooms, beside a pallid, obscure gleam and subdued hush. Prolonged isolation after the process leads to mental deterioration, which is interpreted as a vicious cycle; this deterioration begins with visual and auditory hallucinations, such as hearing footsteps or imagining dim figurines in the peripheral views of a wanderer. The subsequent phase is characterized by persistent persecutory delusions, breaking one's navigation abilities, and directing oneself into deeper regions. Deeper areas are collateral restrictions beside the anomaly, isolating one in pitch-black sight and entrapping one in [[The Void]].

'''Level 321'''<nowiki>’</nowiki>s hotel complex contains numerous accommodations, placed contiguously after each other throughout the halls. These accommodation rooms are austere, with typical furnishings scattered irregularly, yet fairly cramped, thus serving as a relief zone for a brief time. Everyday items can be seen in the rooms, found as half-read books on nightstands, a warm cup of coffee or tea on the table, or a timeworn overcoat on a coat rack. The aforementioned paintings can also be found in the rooms, loosely hanging on the walls; additionally, the paintings within rooms appear to be leaking color or depict portraits of unfamiliar people or a family photo. Moreover, furnishings and decor throughout the rooms inexplicably have unnatural proportions, such as large chairs sunken into the ground or wide nightstands mounted on the walls.

'''Level 321'''<nowiki>’</nowiki>s anomalous nature is deemed interconnected to the [[Achospic Plane]], indirectly causing an excessive amount of psychic noise to accumulate, extracting information from one’s recollection and confabulating it, thus turning it into furnishings, decorations, or hallucinations. This connection is supported via disproportion in the rooms, as they seem to adapt and form into something new on a prolonged continuum. Among these manifestations, diners appear with unusual frequency. Traversing far enough into one of these eventually leads to the exterior of '''Level 321'''.

==The Outside==
{{Blurimage|file=Level321field.png|caption=An ominous sunrise, view from the fields.|hovertext=𝚏𝚒𝚐 3.0}}
This outer region, primarily known as “The Outside,” is a vast expanse of the exterior urban area, with the sky overcast by dense lavender fog. The urban area is depicted as 1970s small towns, typically found in North American suburbs, with entire neighborhoods completely empty, lacking any trace of civilization, such as furnishings and automobiles. The urban area is surrounded by barren wheat fields with pre-autumn vegetation, accompanied by hedgerows and woods stretching beyond the horizon.

Within the suburbs, streets are equipped with streetlights, emitting a glaring daffodil hue intermittently, radiating a warm sense, and wilting into dull asphalt. Through the residences, daffodil hues from the streets seep inside. However, houses are vacant, accompanied by a constant breeze enveloping them. Throughout the vacant rooms, the aforementioned paintings hang on the walls; most illustrate a warm family photo. Traversing further, houses may diverge, slowly morphing into lavender accommodations, eventually leading back to the hotel complex. Either way, being present in the homes for prolonged periods leads to temporary loss of recollection.

