==Attached Note==

<div class="titleblock"><span class="titlebox" style="color: white;">Recovered Note:</span><br>
{{Blurimage|file=Level321diner.png|caption=Sun shines brighter within the diner.|width=600px|align=center|hovertext=𝚏𝚒𝚐 4.0}}
My eyes blurred upon entering the fabulous diner. I sat on the stool with my burden, my backpack sagging behind. I put my elixir on the counter. I was alone, so I took the shot glasses from the shelves and filled them up. ''Almond'' tonic was poured slowly into the glasses; however, I spilled some on the counter, and it dripped, soaking the floor with pale moisture. Tiles stretched and patterned, and the tonic filled it up as if it were a maze, trying to reach a drain with all hopes and no reckoning. What was I doing? I laughed and downed a glass.

A droplet trickled down from my face, ''almond'' mixing with the sweat. I stroked my beard; I guess one glass wasn't enough for my appetite. One more wouldn't hurt. I shook my bottle for a while, and the whirling sounds of the water made me wonder why I shouldn't try to live life. I flipped the bottle in the air. I guess I still didn't age. I poured from the bottle again; the shot glass filled up to the brim and overflowed much more than the last time. A single tile came out of its place and started to drag relentlessly on the soaked ground.

I'm curious: why did the lavender get all over? I wondered why the lavender had spread everywhere as I picked up the floating tile. It's a beautiful quadrilateral until you rotate it, and then it becomes a square. Nothing changed, but you just prefer a simpler name and a different perspective. I put down the tile on the counter; there was a glimpse of color under the tiles. I dragged the object from its tail. It was a vibrant '''daffodil''' that somehow managed to survive since then. I admire it.

Celebratory act, so I downed another glass. Should I leave it within the diner? Or may it bring me charm? My arm slipped, and my bottle rolled off the counter. Fuck! I put the '''daffodil''' on the glass and decided to carry it along in my pocket. I threw myself from the stool with ease and swept across the counter with a napkin. I pushed on the glass doors; a memorable sunset greeted me in sight. I wandered on the pavement, sometimes with icterine streetlights brightening up my way on the streets; the hue drifted to a somber end.

'''321 Lavender Street''' is on the end; I passed from here many times. I mean, these streets probably have different names, but still, I can make up names. It's like a hometown; I can walk around without a thought. A gentle breeze enveloped me, making me feel as if I've cast off the weight of the world. I don't know why, but a childish joy filled me. I smiled towards the horizon and ran into the fields like a kid. I laughed and ran my hands through the wheat. A tart fatigue set in as I lay down on the mellow earth; my eyes started to betray me.

Rise and shine, big man. I felt like shit and alive at the same time; ahh, such a lovely time. I got back into the streets; wonders of the world greeted me. I found this taxi sunk on the road, with steamed-up windows and worn seats. I checked the front seats, and there was an envelope on the car hood. It read, "How's college going? We miss you." Awareness hit me: there wasn't any food in the car, and I was nearly starving. Out of spite, I bit down on the envelope to silence my hunger. The taste of wet paper clung to my throat; I needed to eat something.

Tore apart and crushed, I couldn't mind it. But I choked; my throat swallowed. Frightening end that'll await me? Cough, cough more. I spat it out; it became a pale mush, stuck on the dark asphalt, disgusting. I was out of breath and nauseous. My world blurred, and I got dizzy. I twisted my ankle on the step, and I fell onto the ground. AHH! My jeans oozed red, and I felt a striking pain in my leg. Fumbling in my pockets, a blood-stained '''daffodil''' came out. Glass broke, and shards directly went deep into skin. I needed to close this wound, so I reached for my backpack.

My shoulders were empty, then it hit me. How's the weight of the world suddenly dropped? How did I throw myself off the stools with ease? It was the diner, and now, the backpack is out of my reach. I took out my shirt, and I wrapped it around the wound. Bleeding eased off; pain remained. Shards went too deep to take out and too sharp to disregard. I was desperate but tried to reach for help. Hello? I need help. Can anyone hear me? My sound echoed back, back, and back. Again, again, and again...

Hello? Hello? Hello? It came back. Then, streets went back to silence. Knock, knock. Is anyone home? No response, handle turned, but the door resisted. I searched around for a key, looking in cliché spots, under pots, and under rocks. What was I thinking? Hope for hospitality, even though it never worked before? Out of desperation, I picked up a large rock and threw it on the kitchen window with all my strength. It shattered thousands of pieces, and shards flew into the withered planks, piercing into the floor. I plunged inside, reaching for the sink; water flowed in a trickle. I drank droplets, like I'd never hydrated before.

I felt refreshed. I decided to investigate the inside, entering the living room. I wanted to clear my head after everything I got through. I ran my hands over shelves, leaning into them and roaming around. There was a picture with a cracked silver frame and a faded photo. People whom I don't know, standing beside each other, look like they know each other. I lowered the picture down; the sun shone on my face, glazing my eyes.

There was a comfy armchair that caught my glimpse; it was pearly blue but weirdly sat on something. I knocked it over; there were hundreds of envelopes underneath. Who sent them? Why are they here? A soft cushion with the same tint fell over to the floor. I took the cushion and sat cross-legged as the sunset came closer to its end. The pile of envelopes snatched my interest. I took one from my left and picked up the stained '''daffodil''' with my right. The sunset I greeted shone brighter while revealing the blood on the cushion.


